cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.SY, cs.DC, cs.MM

This paper discusses the statistical multiplexing gain of virtual base station pools in cloud radio access networks, which involves network infrastructure, information theory, and system dynamics. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also involves mathematical modeling and analysis, which suggests cs.IT (Information Theory) as the second likely category. The paper also discusses the constraints imposed by both radio and computational resources, which suggests cs.SY (Systems and Control) as the third likely category. The paper also involves the pooling of multiple virtual base stations, which suggests cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) as the fourth likely category. Finally, the paper also discusses the session-level statistical multiplexing gain of both real-time and delay-tolerant traffic, which suggests cs.MM (Multimedia) as the fifth likely category.
